üíÅüèΩ CERVICAL FACET JOINT SYNDROME! But first.. What the heck‚Äôs a facet joint? üõë Everyone blames disc for back pain but we forget these little guys.

Our spines are made of a column of moveable bones called vertebrae that connect to one another. Each vertebra functions as a three-joint complex with a large disc in the front and two facet joints in the back. This design is strong ‚Äî keeping the bones linked together and letting our spine bend and twist. Healthy facet joints glide and slide as the back moves, but prevent over-twisting.

SO, cervical facet joint syndrome, is a degenerative condition that causes pain and stiffness in the cervical, or neck, region of the spine... These joints provide stability, while also enabling neck movements such as turning or nodding the head.

Degenerative changes in the spine may cause body weight to shift unevenly onto the facet joints, OUCH üò£. This extra weight, like in discs, causes wear and tear on the joint and changes it over time. The joint capsule thins, smooth cartilage breaks down and becomes irregular like a cobblestone street, and bone spurs may form. Check out the picture!

The irritated joint sends pain signals to the brain üß† via small nerves in the capsule called medial branch sensory nerves In turn, the muscles in the area can stiffen and spasm.

TEMPORARY RELIEF!!!!!! When people leave too early, they come back too soon. üëéüèΩ .

When we go to any doctor, usually the goal is to feel better. The same is true when going to a chiropractor. BUT, there‚Äôs a trick. Once we‚Äôre out of pain, the journey is not over! Here‚Äôs what happens.

Symptoms and pain is an alert system for bodies to tell us something is off. After five chiropractic adjustments and therapy sessions we may have no more symptoms, BUT that doesnt mean the issue is fixed yet. Because our bodies have the incredible design to adapt, muscle memory plays a key role in healing. Since our bodies have been adapting to this problem for months or years, NOW we have to focus on biomechanics and muscle memory to TEACH our bodies how to function properly. If we skip this strengthening step, we go back to the place we were!

Cervical disc degeneration is not something that can be cured long term, but with decompression and traction therapy, we‚Äôre able to manage and relieve the painful symptoms of it! By its robotic pulling and releasing motion, we take pressure off the spinal discs by creating negative pressure. As a result, bulging or herniated disks may retract, taking pressure off nerves and other structures in the spine! This in turn, helps promote the flow and proper movement of water, oxygen, and nutrient-rich fluids into the disks so they can heal!

We all would like to have some curves.. üòâ BUT ARE YOU THINKING ABOUT THE NECK?!
.
.
In current society we live in, our necks are constantly flexed forward on our phones, at desks, and looking downward. This puts a lot of added pressure on the cervical spine and over time our necks can loose their curve. Any degree forward our neck travels, it‚Äôs adding 10, 20, 30, 40 pounds of pressure on the discs in our necks, and therefore, making them smaller. This can cause impingement on nerves, tension in muscles, and biomechanically, the neck won't move how it‚Äôs supposed to.

As chiropractors, when we adjust, we help to restore that curve to take that pressure off the dics. That way they aren't being worn down as fast. We also like to make sure the neck muscles are loose when we adjust so they aren't pulling the spine in improper ways.

Cervical degenerative disc disease is a common cause of neck pain and radiating arm pain! It develops when one or more of the discs in the cervical spine starts to break down due to wear and tear. Despite its name, degenerative disc disease is not a disease, but a natural occurrence that comes with aging. üëéüèª
.
‚¨áÔ∏è SYMPTOMS
-neck pain
-radiating arm pain
-decreased neck range of motion
-stiffness
-numbness
-tingling in arms and/ or hands
-weakness in the neck, arms, or hands
.
Disc degenerration can be suspected through symptoms but ocnfirmed by diagnostic imaging!
.
If degenerative disc disease is present, the images will often show a narrowing of the spaces between your vertebrae, which indicates that one or more discs have thinned or collapsed. Check out the picture above!
.

Neurotransmitters control virtually all of the body's functions, from hormones to digestion to feeling happy, sad, or stressed. But what we don't normally think about is how our thoughts are the main driving force in the neurotransmitters we produce.. Everyone can admit that when in a negative mindset, it‚Äôs easiest to continue thinking negatively. But what flows through your mind also sculpts your brain in permanent ways.

Every thought that crosses our minds causes neurochemical changes, some temporary and some lasting. Like when people consciously practice gratitude, they get a surge of rewarding neurotransmitters, like dopamine, and experience a general brightening of the mind, probably correlated with more of the neurochemical norepinephrine.

When there is an injury or trauma, the body changes the way muscles work and how the joints move, in order to help pick up the slack for the weakened area. This is a temporary fix and can last for months or even years. There comes a time though, when those muscles and joints can no longer pick up the slack. That is usually when symptoms begin (low back pain, hip pain, shoulder pain, headaches, etc.)!
.
After the first adjustment, people expect to feel BETTER. So when the pain does not change or, in some cases, gets worse, frustration and confusion happens. What we want to STRESS to our patients is after the first adjustment, DON'T BE ALARMEDüö® if the pain gets a little worse the next day.
.
It‚Äôs like getting back into an exercise routine for the first time after a long layoff. Your muscles and ligaments in your body are going to be a little sore because they aren‚Äôt used to being stretched and strengthened. The same thing happens after an adjustment. Your body is beginning to reset itself and is correcting muscles and ligaments and starting the road back to ‚Äúnormal‚Äù function.
